The Philippines and its foreign creditorbanks will sign formal documents in mid-July to restructurepart of its debt, the Central Bank said.    A spokesman told reporters the documents would formalisethe agreement reached in March on the restructuring of 10.3billion dlrs, out of a total foreign debt of 28.2 billion.    The interest rate spread agreed was 7/8 of a percentagepoint over LIBOR. The spokesman gave no date for the signing.    Manila had demanded a renegotiation after Argentina won a13/16 of a percentage point spread, but it later dropped thisdemand. REUTER&#3;